        Launching Your Brisbane Property Campaign: How the First Open Home and First Week Define the Result
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        The first seven days of a sale campaign disproportionately shape the result. Here is what happens in week one, why the first open home matters so much, and what serious sellers do to be ready.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most sale campaigns in Brisbane's inner east are effectively decided in the first seven to fourteen days. The buyers who produce the best results are rarely casual browsers who stumble across your listing in week five. They are the buyers who have been actively searching in your suburb for weeks or months, watching new listings closely, and turning up for the first open home. That pool of prepared buyers cycles through quickly, and most of the meaningful activity on a campaign happens while those buyers are still engaged.</p>

      <p>Sellers who treat the first week as just the beginning of a long process usually underperform. Sellers who treat it as the peak of the campaign consistently produce stronger results. The practical implication is that everything the seller and agent do should be calibrated to being fully ready on day one, not day fifteen.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why the first week matters so much</h2>

      <p>Serious buyers in any given suburb and price bracket tend to operate as a small, watchful group. They have set up their portal alerts, they have already seen most of the existing listings, and they know what is available. When a new property appears that matches their brief, they react quickly. The first open home is often the highest-value forty five minutes of the entire campaign because this is when that cohort shows up in person.</p>

      <p>The same listing that looks fresh and compelling in week one starts to look stale by week four. Buyers who saw it early and passed are unlikely to revisit it. New buyers entering the market look at it alongside listings that launched recently and question why it has not sold. A listing that was once the most interesting thing in the search results becomes one of several options. Inquiry volume typically halves after the first two weeks, and the quality of that inquiry usually drops with it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What actually happens in week one</h2>

      <p>A well-executed launch follows a predictable rhythm. The listing goes live on realestate.com.au and domain.com.au, usually on a Wednesday or Thursday so it appears fresh to weekend searchers. Signage goes up on the property. Print advertising, if part of the campaign, hits homes and letterboxes. Social media boosts push the listing to targeted audiences. The first open home is scheduled for the first Saturday, occasionally the Saturday following if preparation is still being finalised.</p>

      <p>Serious buyers inspect on that Saturday. The agent follows up with every inspector within 24 to 48 hours, probing for genuine interest, price feedback, and next steps. The seller receives a campaign report summarising inquiry numbers, inspection quality, online activity, and the agent's read on the market's response. Offers from keen buyers sometimes arrive before the first week ends, particularly for strongly presented properties that are accurately priced.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens in week two</h2>

      <p>Week two is when the buyers who attended week one turn into negotiators. The agent converts inspections into offers, finance, and pest and building inspections. A second open home refreshes the buyer pool by catching anyone who missed the first, and it gives serious buyers a reason to return with a partner, a builder, or a financial advisor. Most well-run campaigns produce their first genuine offers between day eight and day fourteen.</p>

      <p>This is also the point at which the seller needs to be clear-headed about pricing, terms, and timing. Strong offers early in the campaign are a signal to engage, not to wait indefinitely for something better. In most Brisbane inner-east suburbs, the first strong offer is a reasonable proxy for what the market is prepared to pay, and holding out for a higher number beyond that point often costs more than it gains.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens after week two</h2>

      <p>From week three onwards, inquiry volume typically falls. The urgency of the launch has passed. Buyers still entering the market tend to be more price-sensitive, more cautious, or still exploring. The agent's job shifts from managing demand to generating it: refreshing the portal listing, booking buyers for individual inspections, contacting databases, and keeping the property visible.</p>

      <p>Campaigns that extend into weeks four, five, and six without an offer are usually signalling that something is not right. Price is the most common issue. Presentation, positioning, or marketing quality can also be the culprit. Sellers who read that signal early and adjust tend to recover the campaign. Sellers who hold firm and wait for a miracle buyer usually find that days on market creep up and price eventually follows.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why the first open home matters most</h2>

      <p>The first open home is the peak day for serious, prepared buyers. It is the moment when the highest concentration of likely purchasers walks through the property at the same time. The size and quality of that crowd affect perception: a busy open home tells every buyer in the room that demand is real, which changes how they bid, how quickly they move, and how hard they negotiate. A sparse first open home has the opposite effect.</p>

      <p>Getting the first open home right is partly about attendance, partly about presentation. Attendance comes from strong photography, accurate pricing, clear marketing, and good timing. Presentation is about how the property looks on the day: clean, decluttered, styled to the level the price bracket expects, warm lighting, thoughtful scent, and calm, confident hosting from the agent. None of this is expensive, but it requires preparation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers must have ready by launch</h2>

      <p>The non-negotiable list before going live: professional photography shot in good conditions (ideally soft morning or late-afternoon light, never grey midday), a crisp and honest listing description, a professionally drawn 2D floor plan, compliance certificates (pool safety, smoke alarms) available on request, a well-presented home with decluttering and any necessary styling complete, and the contract of sale prepared by the seller's solicitor and ready to be issued to a serious buyer.</p>

      <p>The common mistake is launching early because the agent has said there are buyers waiting. There are always buyers waiting. What matters is that the property is presented in a way that converts those buyers when they do appear. Rushing to market with placeholder photography, a half-styled home, or an incomplete contract wastes the first week and leaves the seller trying to recover in weeks two and three with a weaker buyer pool.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What most campaigns do wrong in week one</h2>

      <p>Four mistakes recur. The first is launching without final professional photography, hoping to update later. Buyers form a first impression from the hero image, and a weak hero image means fewer clicks, fewer saves, and a thinner first open home. The second is pricing unrealistically high in the hope of catching a motivated outlier. Serious buyers with data filter the listing out immediately, and the agent is left trying to work with tyre-kickers.</p>

      <p>The third is understaffing the first open home. One agent trying to greet, qualify, and build rapport with 25 or 30 buyers across 45 minutes is not enough. A good launch has two agents on the floor, one at the door and one moving with buyers. The fourth is failing to follow up quickly. Every inspector needs a personal call within 24 to 48 hours. Agents who skip this step lose buyers to competitors whose agents call back the same day.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a well-executed launch looks like</h2>

      <p>The listing goes live on a Wednesday or Thursday to catch weekend searchers. The photography, floor plan, description, and signage are all final and professional. The first open home is on the first Saturday, fully staffed, well presented, and timed to avoid clashes with major inspections in the same price bracket. The agent personally calls every inspector by the following Monday with honest, specific feedback.</p>

      <p>A second open home on the following Saturday maintains momentum and gives buyers a reason to return. Offers are requested and evaluated in week two, with a clear process for the seller to review, negotiate, and accept. Communication from the agent is daily, structured, and honest about what is working and what is not. The seller feels informed rather than managed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to do if the first week underperforms</h2>

      <p>One soft open home is not a disaster. The data is too thin to draw firm conclusions after a single weekend. The right response is to review what the first week actually produced: inquiry volume, inspection attendance, online engagement, feedback from buyers, and the quality of the offers (if any). Then identify whether the issue is price, presentation, or positioning.</p>

      <p>Small adjustments often restore momentum in week two: refining the marketing copy, replacing a weak hero image, adjusting the price guide by a small amount, adding a targeted social media boost, or extending open home hours. Sellers who panic and drop the price by 10% after one slow open home almost always regret it. Sellers who ignore the signal entirely and refuse to adjust almost always pay for it in weeks four and beyond.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>

      <p>The first week is when the most serious, most prepared buyers engage with the listing. The size of the buyer pool in week one is larger and better qualified than at any other point in the campaign. Everything a seller does should be calibrated to that reality. Preparation, presentation, pricing, and execution all matter more on day one than on day thirty.</p>

      <p>Waste the first week and the campaign spends the rest of its life working with a thinner, less prepared buyer pool. Use it well and most campaigns in the inner east produce a strong offer within the first fortnight. The difference is rarely market luck. It is almost always preparation.</p>

